# SSH Key Generation & Passwordless Authentication

## Overview
This project demonstrates how to generate SSH key pairs and enable passwordless authentication between Linux systems using `ssh-keygen`.

---

## Steps Performed

### 1. Generate SSH Key Pair
```bash
ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -C "your_email@example.com"
```

- Key stored in: `~/.ssh/id_rsa`  
- Public key: `~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub`

---

### 2. Copy Public Key to Remote Server
```bash
ssh-copy-id user@remote_host
```

OR manually:
```bash
cat ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub | ssh user@remote_host "mkdir -p ~/.ssh && cat >> ~/.ssh/authorized_keys"
```

---

### 3. Set Permissions (Remote Machine)
```bash
chmod 700 ~/.ssh
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/authorized_keys
```

---

### 4. Test SSH Login
```bash
ssh user@remote_host
```

---

## 🚀 Outcome

- Successfully enabled passwordless SSH authentication between Linux systems  
- Strengthened system security using key-based authentication instead of passwords  
- Simplified and streamlined remote Linux server access and management  

---

## 💡 Best Practices

- Prefer `ed25519` keys instead of RSA:
```bash
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your_email@example.com"
```

- Always test login after setup:
```bash
ssh user@remote_host
```

- Maintain correct SSH permissions:
```bash
chmod 700 ~/.ssh
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/authorized_keys
```
